"{\n  \"project_key\": \"STLSB\",\n  \"feature_name\": \"SPDM Attestation (LPC55S69 MCU)\",\n  \"open_questions\": [\n    \"Which specific LPC55S69 or LPC55S3x variant is the final target MCU?\",\n    \"What is the MCU's I2C slave address and MCTP EID assignment?\",\n    \"How does the MCU determine the active JKR firmware boot slot?\",\n    \"What is the Cornelis root CA key ceremony and HSM infrastructure?\",\n    \"What is the BMC's SPDM Requester implementation and version?\",\n    \"Is FreeRTOS confirmed as the MCU RTOS, or are alternatives still under consideration?\",\n    \"What is the SPI flash bus arbitration mechanism when both JKR ASIC and MCU access the flash simultaneously?\",\n    \"What is the MCU firmware update delivery mechanism in Phase 3?\"\n  ],\n  \"assumptions\": [\n    \"NXP LPC55S69 board with SPI flash tap and SMBus connections is available and functional\",\n    \"FreeRTOS is the selected RTOS for the MCU firmware\",\n    \"libspdm v3.8.1 with Mbed TLS crypto backend\",\n    \"MCU operates as read-only observer of JKR SPI flash\",\n    \"No modifications to JKR Xtensa firmware required or permitted\",\n    \"BMC has functional SPDM 1.2 Requester implementation\",\n    \"SHA-256 mandatory; SHA-384 optional. ECC P-256 for signing\",\n    \"Single certificate slot (slot 0)\",\n    \"Intel CSS headers included in measurement boundaries\",\n    \"VPD treated as mutable measurement\",\n    \"OCP Attestation v1.0 compliance required\",\n    \"Static MCTP EID allocation\",\n    \"Greenfield project \u2014 no existing MCU firmware\"\n  ],\n  \"folded_items\": [\n    {\n      \"original\": \"Validate SPI flash tap hardware\",\n      \"folded_into\": \"SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap) and MCU project scaffolding\",\n      \"reason\": \"Primary verb is 'validate' \u2014 lab activity, not a code branch (Rule 7)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"original\": \"Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation\",\n      \"folded_into\": \"I2C/SMBus slave driver and MCU project scaffolding\",\n      \"reason\": \"Primary verb is 'validate' \u2014 lab activity, not a code branch (Rule 7)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"original\": \"Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board\",\n      \"folded_into\": \"CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\",\n      \"reason\": \"Primary verb is 'benchmark' \u2014 lab activity, not a code branch (Rule 7)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"original\": \"All 7 measurement indices populated & verified\",\n      \"folded_into\": \"Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\",\n      \"reason\": \"Primary verb is 'populated & verified' \u2014 verification activity, not a separate code branch (Rule 7)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"original\": \"Debug lockdown (CMPA/CFPA configuration)\",\n      \"folded_into\": \"MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\",\n      \"reason\": \"Configuration-only item \u2014 done on same branch as secure boot (Rule 6)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"original\": \"Real SMBus integration (MCU \u2194 BMC on hardware)\",\n      \"folded_into\": \"MCTP over SMBus transport layer and libspdm Responder integration\",\n      \"reason\": \"Integration testing on hardware \u2014 not a separate code branch (Rules 3 and 7)\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"epics\": [\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"[SPDM] SPI Flash & Measurement\",\n      \"description\": \"## Overview\\nThis epic covers the SPI flash reading capability and firmware measurement engine for SPDM attestation. The MCU reads JKR SPI flash contents via a hardware tap and computes SHA-256 hashes over 7 measurement indices (MCU FW, JKR CPORT active, JKR UEFI, JKR config, JKR VPD, JKR eFuse key hash, platform HW version).\\n\\n## Functional Thread\\nDefine measurement manifest \u2192 SPI flash read driver \u2192 Active/inactive boot slot detection \u2192 Measurement engine. This is a vertical slice from measurement definition through flash reading to hash computation.\\n\\n## Cross-Epic Dependencies\\n- SPI flash read driver is BLOCKED_BY MCU project scaffolding ([SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration)\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- How does the MCU determine the active JKR firmware boot slot?\\n- What is the SPI flash bus arbitration mechanism when both JKR ASIC and MCU access the flash simultaneously?\",\n      \"components\": [\"firmware\", \"tools\"],\n      \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\"],\n      \"stories\": [\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[TOOL] Define measurement manifest\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nDefine and commit the measurement manifest specifying all 7 measurement indices, their SPI flash boundaries (start address, length), hash algorithm, measurement type (immutable/mutable), and Intel CSS header inclusion policy. This produces a committed manifest file (e.g., `measurement_manifest.json`) that the measurement engine will consume at build time.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe measurement manifest is the single source of truth for what the MCU measures and how. It must be defined and reviewed before the measurement engine is implemented, as it drives the engine's configuration. The JKR SPI flash layout mapping must be documented to ensure correct measurement boundaries.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: None (root item)\\n- RELATED_TO: Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\\n\\n## Scope Items Included\\n- Define measurement manifest (from scope)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] All 7 measurement indices defined with flash address, length, hash algorithm, and type\\n- [ ] JKR SPI flash layout documented: UEFI@0x000000, CPORT active@0x220000, CPORT inactive@0x320000, Config@0x2A0000, VPD@0x208000\\n- [ ] Intel CSS header inclusion policy documented (full image including header)\\n- [ ] VPD marked as mutable measurement type; all others immutable\\n- [ ] Manifest committed as a versioned file (JSON or equivalent) in the repo\\n- [ ] Manifest reviewed and approved by firmware and security leads\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for manifest schema validation (e.g., JSON schema or build-time check)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"tools\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-high\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"high\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"All 7 measurement indices defined with flash address, length, hash algorithm, and type\",\n            \"JKR SPI flash layout documented: UEFI@0x000000, CPORT active@0x220000, CPORT inactive@0x320000, Config@0x2A0000, VPD@0x208000\",\n            \"Intel CSS header inclusion policy documented (full image including header)\",\n            \"VPD marked as mutable measurement type; all others immutable\",\n            \"Manifest committed as a versioned file (JSON or equivalent) in the repo\",\n            \"Manifest reviewed and approved by firmware and security leads\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for manifest schema validation\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement SPI master driver on the LPC55S69 to read JKR SPI flash contents via the hardware tap. Support reading all relevant flash regions: UEFI, CPORT (active/inactive), Config, VPD. The driver must be non-destructive (read-only).\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe measurement engine requires raw flash data to compute hashes. The SPI flash tap provides read-only access to JKR flash without modifying JKR firmware. This driver is the data source for all 7 measurement indices that reference SPI flash content.\\n\\n## Folded Items\\n- **Validate SPI flash tap hardware** (scope item, S, high confidence): The hardware validation (signal integrity, read capability at all regions) is performed as part of driver bring-up and captured in acceptance criteria below. No separate branch needed.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake) \u2014 [SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration epic\\n- RELATED_TO: Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCU reads data from all JKR SPI flash regions matching independent flash dump\\n- [ ] Read operations are non-destructive (read-only confirmed \u2014 no write capability from MCU side)\\n- [ ] Driver handles SPI flash status register and busy states\\n- [ ] Read known pattern from flash and verify correctness\\n- [ ] SPI flash tap signal integrity validated at operational clock speed\\n- [ ] MCU can read known data patterns from all JKR SPI flash regions (UEFI@0x000000, CPORT@0x220000, Config@0x2A0000, VPD@0x208000)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for SPI read operations (mock SPI peripheral for host-side tests)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"MCU reads data from all JKR SPI flash regions matching independent flash dump\",\n            \"Read operations are non-destructive (read-only confirmed \u2014 no write capability from MCU side)\",\n            \"Driver handles SPI flash status register and busy states\",\n            \"Read known pattern from flash and verify correctness\",\n            \"SPI flash tap signal integrity validated at operational clock speed\",\n            \"MCU can read known data patterns from all JKR SPI flash regions (UEFI@0x000000, CPORT@0x220000, Config@0x2A0000, VPD@0x208000)\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for SPI read operations (mock SPI peripheral for host-side tests)\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] Active/inactive boot slot detection\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement logic for the MCU to determine which JKR firmware slot (CPORT active@0x220000 vs inactive@0x320000) is currently active, so the measurement engine hashes the correct firmware image.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nJKR supports A/B firmware slots. The measurement engine must hash the active slot to produce correct attestation measurements. Incorrect slot detection would result in measurement mismatches and attestation failures.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\\n- RELATED_TO: Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCU correctly identifies active CPORT slot by reading slot metadata from SPI flash\\n- [ ] Measurement engine hashes the active slot only\\n- [ ] Slot detection works after JKR firmware update (slot swap)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for slot detection logic (mock flash data for both slot configurations)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"MCU correctly identifies active CPORT slot by reading slot metadata from SPI flash\",\n            \"Measurement engine hashes the active slot only\",\n            \"Slot detection works after JKR firmware update (slot swap)\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for slot detection logic (mock flash data for both slot configurations)\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement the measurement engine that reads and hashes each of the 7 measurement indices: MCU FW (0x01), JKR CPORT active (0x02), JKR UEFI (0x03), JKR config (0x04), JKR VPD (0x05), JKR eFuse key hash (0x06), platform HW version (0x07). Uses SHA-256 (mandatory) with SHA-384 optional. Consumes the measurement manifest to determine flash boundaries and measurement types.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe measurement engine is the core of SPDM attestation \u2014 it produces the cryptographic evidence that the BMC's SPDM Requester verifies. Correct measurements are essential for platform integrity verification per OCP Attestation v1.0.\\n\\n## Folded Items\\n- **All 7 measurement indices populated & verified** (scope item, L, medium confidence): The population and verification of all 7 indices is the primary deliverable of this Story. Verification against independent flash dumps is captured in acceptance criteria below.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Define measurement manifest\\n- BLOCKED_BY: SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Active/inactive boot slot detection\\n- RELATED_TO: libspdm Responder integration (consumes measurements)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] All 7 measurement indices produce correct SHA-256 hashes\\n- [ ] Hashes match independent verification (flash dump + sha256sum)\\n- [ ] Measurement boundaries match manifest (full image including CSS header)\\n- [ ] VPD measurement marked as mutable type; all others immutable\\n- [ ] Measurement refresh on demand (re-read and re-hash)\\n- [ ] Active CPORT slot correctly identified and measured (not inactive slot)\\n- [ ] GET_MEASUREMENTS returns all indices correctly when integrated with libspdm\\n- [ ] Measurement manifest matches implementation\\n- [ ] SHA-384 supported as optional negotiable algorithm\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for hash computation (known input \u2192 known hash) and manifest parsing\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-l\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"L\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"All 7 measurement indices produce correct SHA-256 hashes\",\n            \"Hashes match independent verification (flash dump + sha256sum)\",\n            \"Measurement boundaries match manifest (full image including CSS header)\",\n            \"VPD measurement marked as mutable type; all others immutable\",\n            \"Measurement refresh on demand (re-read and re-hash)\",\n            \"Active CPORT slot correctly identified and measured (not inactive slot)\",\n            \"GET_MEASUREMENTS returns all indices correctly when integrated with libspdm\",\n            \"Measurement manifest matches implementation\",\n            \"SHA-384 supported as optional negotiable algorithm\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for hash computation and manifest parsing\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"Define measurement manifest\", \"SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\", \"Active/inactive boot slot detection\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"[SPDM] PKI & Certificate Management\",\n      \"description\": \"## Overview\\nThis epic covers the X.509 PKI design, certificate slot management, and deployment of Cornelis CA-signed certificate chains for SPDM attestation. The MCU serves a certificate chain (device cert \u2192 intermediate CA \u2192 Cornelis root CA) to the BMC's SPDM Requester.\\n\\n## Functional Thread\\nDesign Cornelis CA hierarchy \u2192 Certificate slot management \u2192 Real certificate chain. This is a vertical slice from PKI design through certificate storage to production deployment.\\n\\n## Cross-Epic Dependencies\\n- Certificate slot management is BLOCKED_BY PUF key enrollment & device key derivation ([SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration)\\n- Design Cornelis CA hierarchy is a root item with no upstream dependencies\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- What is the Cornelis root CA key ceremony and HSM infrastructure?\",\n      \"components\": [\"firmware\", \"tools\"],\n      \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\"],\n      \"stories\": [\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[TOOL] Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nDesign the X.509 PKI hierarchy for SPDM attestation: Cornelis root CA \u2192 intermediate CA \u2192 device identity certificate. Define certificate templates, key usage extensions, validity periods, and OID assignments. Produce committed design documentation and certificate template files.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe PKI hierarchy must be designed and reviewed before device certificates can be generated or provisioned. This is a prerequisite for certificate slot management and factory provisioning. OCP Attestation v1.0 compliance requires specific certificate structures.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: None (root item)\\n- RELATED_TO: Certificate slot management, Real certificate chain, Factory provisioning automation\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Root CA, intermediate CA, and device cert templates defined and committed (e.g., OpenSSL config files or JSON templates)\\n- [ ] Key usage includes digitalSignature for device cert\\n- [ ] Certificate chain validates with `openssl verify`\\n- [ ] OCP Attestation v1.0 compliance verified against specification\\n- [ ] Validity periods and OID assignments documented\\n- [ ] Design document committed to repo (e.g., `docs/pki-hierarchy.md`)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for certificate template generation (template produces valid X.509)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"tools\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-high\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"high\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"Root CA, intermediate CA, and device cert templates defined and committed\",\n            \"Key usage includes digitalSignature for device cert\",\n            \"Certificate chain validates with openssl verify\",\n            \"OCP Attestation v1.0 compliance verified against specification\",\n            \"Validity periods and OID assignments documented\",\n            \"Design document committed to repo (e.g., docs/pki-hierarchy.md)\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for certificate template generation\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] Certificate slot management\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement certificate slot 0 management: store and serve X.509 certificate chain (device cert \u2192 intermediate CA \u2192 Cornelis root CA) to SPDM Requester via GET_DIGESTS and GET_CERTIFICATE. Single slot only.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nSPDM attestation requires the Responder to serve its certificate chain to the Requester for identity verification. The certificate slot is the storage and retrieval mechanism that libspdm callbacks will use to respond to GET_DIGESTS and GET_CERTIFICATE requests.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\\n- BLOCKED_BY: PUF key enrollment & device key derivation \u2014 [SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration epic\\n- RELATED_TO: libspdm Responder integration, Real certificate chain\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] GET_DIGESTS returns correct hash of certificate chain\\n- [ ] GET_CERTIFICATE returns complete chain (device + intermediate + root)\\n- [ ] `openssl verify` validates the chain successfully\\n- [ ] Certificate key usage includes digitalSignature\\n- [ ] Slot 0 storage handles certificate chain up to expected maximum size\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for certificate storage, retrieval, and digest computation\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"GET_DIGESTS returns correct hash of certificate chain\",\n            \"GET_CERTIFICATE returns complete chain (device + intermediate + root)\",\n            \"openssl verify validates the chain successfully\",\n            \"Certificate key usage includes digitalSignature\",\n            \"Slot 0 storage handles certificate chain up to expected maximum size\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for certificate storage, retrieval, and digest computation\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\", \"PUF key enrollment & device key derivation\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] Real certificate chain (Cornelis CA-signed)\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nReplace test certificates with a real Cornelis CA-signed certificate chain: device cert (signed by intermediate CA) \u2192 intermediate CA cert \u2192 Cornelis root CA cert. Deploy to MCU slot 0. Each device gets a unique device certificate bound to its PUF-derived key.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nProduction SPDM attestation requires real CA-signed certificates, not self-signed test certs. The BMC must be able to validate the certificate chain against the Cornelis root CA to establish trust in the MCU's identity.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Certificate slot management\\n- RELATED_TO: Factory provisioning automation\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Device certificate signed by Cornelis intermediate CA\\n- [ ] Full chain validates with `openssl verify` against Cornelis root CA\\n- [ ] BMC accepts and validates the certificate chain during SPDM flow\\n- [ ] Each device has a unique device certificate (bound to PUF-derived key)\\n- [ ] Certificate chain deployed to MCU slot 0\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for certificate chain validation logic\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"Device certificate signed by Cornelis intermediate CA\",\n            \"Full chain validates with openssl verify against Cornelis root CA\",\n            \"BMC accepts and validates the certificate chain during SPDM flow\",\n            \"Each device has a unique device certificate (bound to PUF-derived key)\",\n            \"Certificate chain deployed to MCU slot 0\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for certificate chain validation logic\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\", \"Certificate slot management\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"[SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration\",\n      \"description\": \"## Overview\\nThis epic is the primary SPDM development thread: MCU project scaffolding, crypto backend, I2C/SMBus driver, MCTP transport, PUF key enrollment, and libspdm Responder integration. It delivers the end-to-end SPDM 1.2 Responder capability on the LPC55S69 MCU.\\n\\n## Functional Thread\\nMCU project scaffolding \u2192 CASPER crypto backend \u2192 PUF key enrollment (crypto branch)\\nMCU project scaffolding \u2192 I2C/SMBus slave driver \u2192 MCTP over SMBus transport (transport branch)\\nBoth branches converge at \u2192 libspdm Responder integration \u2192 ResponseNotReady + Error handling\\n\\n## Cross-Epic Dependencies\\n- This epic's MCU project scaffolding is depended on by: SPI flash read driver ([SPDM] SPI Flash & Measurement), MCU secure boot ([SPDM] Secure Boot & Provisioning)\\n- This epic's PUF key enrollment is depended on by: Certificate slot management ([SPDM] PKI & Certificate Management), Factory provisioning automation ([SPDM] Secure Boot & Provisioning)\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- Which specific LPC55S69 or LPC55S3x variant is the final target MCU?\\n- What is the MCU's I2C slave address and MCTP EID assignment?\\n- Is FreeRTOS confirmed as the MCU RTOS?\\n- What is the BMC's SPDM Requester implementation and version?\",\n      \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n      \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\"],\n      \"stories\": [\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nCreate the MCU firmware project structure with FreeRTOS, NXP MCUXpresso SDK for LPC55S69, and CMake build system. Include basic main(), FreeRTOS task creation, clock/pin configuration, and host-side cross-compilation setup.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThis is the foundation for all MCU firmware development. Every other firmware Story depends on this scaffolding. The build system must support both target cross-compilation (arm-none-eabi-gcc) and host-side unit test compilation.\\n\\n## Folded Items\\n- **Validate SPI flash tap hardware** (scope item, S, high confidence): SPI flash tap hardware validation is a prerequisite lab activity. Its acceptance criteria (MCU can read known data patterns from all JKR SPI flash regions, read-only access confirmed, signal integrity validated) are captured on the SPI flash read driver Story.\\n- **Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation** (scope item, S, high confidence): SMBus topology validation is a prerequisite lab activity. Its acceptance criteria (MCU responds to I2C address scan, static EID assigned, BMC can distinguish endpoints) are captured on the I2C/SMBus slave driver Story.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: None (root item \u2014 upstream validate/benchmark items are lab activities folded into downstream Stories)\\n- RELATED_TO: All firmware Stories depend on this scaffolding\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] CMake build succeeds with arm-none-eabi-gcc, producing valid ELF binary\\n- [ ] FreeRTOS boots on LPC55S69 eval board\\n- [ ] LED blink or UART hello-world confirms execution\\n- [ ] Build system supports host-side unit test compilation (native gcc)\\n- [ ] Clock and pin configuration for SPI, I2C, and UART peripherals\\n- [ ] Project structure follows Cornelis firmware conventions (src/, include/, test/, docs/)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for build system (CMake configure + build succeeds in CI)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: S\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-high\", \"complexity-s\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"S\",\n          \"confidence\": \"high\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"CMake build succeeds with arm-none-eabi-gcc, producing valid ELF binary\",\n            \"FreeRTOS boots on LPC55S69 eval board\",\n            \"LED blink or UART hello-world confirms execution\",\n            \"Build system supports host-side unit test compilation (native gcc)\",\n            \"Clock and pin configuration for SPI, I2C, and UART peripherals\",\n            \"Project structure follows Cornelis firmware conventions\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for build system validation\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement an Mbed TLS alternative (ALT) backend that routes ECC P-256 and SHA-256/SHA-384 operations through the LPC55S69 CASPER hardware accelerator. Validate against NIST CAVP test vectors.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nSPDM attestation requires cryptographic operations (signing challenges, hashing measurements) that must be hardware-accelerated to meet response timing requirements. The CASPER accelerator provides the necessary performance for ECC P-256 and SHA operations.\\n\\n## Folded Items\\n- **Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board** (scope item, M, high confidence): Benchmarking is performed as part of the crypto backend bring-up. Results inform the ResponseNotReady timeout design. Acceptance criteria below capture the benchmarking requirements.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\\n- RELATED_TO: PUF key enrollment, libspdm Responder integration, ResponseNotReady mechanism\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] ECC P-256 key generation, sign, and verify pass NIST CAVP test vectors\\n- [ ] SHA-256 and SHA-384 pass NIST CAVP test vectors\\n- [ ] All operations use CASPER hardware (no software fallback in production path)\\n- [ ] Mbed TLS self-test suite passes with CASPER backend\\n- [ ] ECC P-256 sign/verify latency measured and documented (ms)\\n- [ ] SHA-256 and SHA-384 throughput measured and documented (MB/s)\\n- [ ] CASPER SHA-256 throughput meets SPDM timing budget (benchmark results with statistical confidence)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for all crypto operations (CAVP vectors + round-trip sign/verify)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-l\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"L\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"ECC P-256 key generation, sign, and verify pass NIST CAVP test vectors\",\n            \"SHA-256 and SHA-384 pass NIST CAVP test vectors\",\n            \"All operations use CASPER hardware (no software fallback in production path)\",\n            \"Mbed TLS self-test suite passes with CASPER backend\",\n            \"ECC P-256 sign/verify latency measured and documented (ms)\",\n            \"SHA-256 and SHA-384 throughput measured and documented (MB/s)\",\n            \"CASPER SHA-256 throughput meets SPDM timing budget\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for all crypto operations (CAVP vectors + round-trip sign/verify)\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] I2C/SMBus slave driver (MCU as MCTP endpoint)\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement I2C slave mode driver on the LPC55S69 for receiving MCTP-over-SMBus packets from the BMC. Handle SMBus block read/write protocol, byte-level framing, and interrupt-driven reception.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe I2C/SMBus slave driver is the physical transport layer for SPDM communication. The BMC sends MCTP packets over SMBus to the MCU, which must receive and respond to them reliably.\\n\\n## Folded Items\\n- **Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation** (scope item, S, high confidence): SMBus topology validation and EID allocation are lab activities performed during driver bring-up. Acceptance criteria below capture the validation requirements.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\\n- RELATED_TO: MCTP over SMBus transport layer\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCU receives I2C transactions at configured slave address\\n- [ ] SMBus block write/read protocol correctly handled\\n- [ ] I2C loopback test passes (send known data, verify reception)\\n- [ ] No blocking in ISR \u2014 DMA or interrupt-driven with FreeRTOS notification\\n- [ ] MCU responds to I2C address scan from BMC\\n- [ ] Static EID assigned to MCU that does not conflict with JKR ASIC EID\\n- [ ] BMC can distinguish MCU endpoint from JKR ASIC endpoint\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for I2C slave driver (mock I2C peripheral for host-side tests)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"MCU receives I2C transactions at configured slave address\",\n            \"SMBus block write/read protocol correctly handled\",\n            \"I2C loopback test passes (send known data, verify reception)\",\n            \"No blocking in ISR \u2014 DMA or interrupt-driven with FreeRTOS notification\",\n            \"MCU responds to I2C address scan from BMC\",\n            \"Static EID assigned to MCU that does not conflict with JKR ASIC EID\",\n            \"BMC can distinguish MCU endpoint from JKR ASIC endpoint\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for I2C slave driver\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] PUF key enrollment & device key derivation\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement PUF (Physically Unclonable Function) enrollment on the LPC55S69 to derive a unique ECC P-256 device signing key. Key is deterministically derived from PUF SRAM pattern and stored activation code.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nEach MCU needs a unique device identity for SPDM attestation. The PUF provides a hardware root of trust \u2014 the private key is derived from the chip's physical characteristics and never stored in flash, making it resistant to extraction.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\\n- RELATED_TO: Certificate slot management, Factory provisioning automation\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] PUF enrollment produces activation code\\n- [ ] Key derivation from PUF is deterministic across power cycles\\n- [ ] Derived ECC P-256 key pair is valid (sign/verify round-trip)\\n- [ ] Private key never appears in flash or debug output\\n- [ ] Activation code stored securely in protected flash region\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for key derivation determinism and key validity\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-l\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"L\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"PUF enrollment produces activation code\",\n            \"Key derivation from PUF is deterministic across power cycles\",\n            \"Derived ECC P-256 key pair is valid (sign/verify round-trip)\",\n            \"Private key never appears in flash or debug output\",\n            \"Activation code stored securely in protected flash region\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for key derivation determinism and key validity\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] MCTP over SMBus transport layer\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement MCTP transport binding over SMBus per DMTF DSP0237. Handle MCTP packet assembly/disassembly, message fragmentation, medium-specific header, and EID-based addressing on top of the I2C slave driver.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nMCTP is the transport protocol that carries SPDM messages between the BMC and MCU. The SMBus binding (DSP0237) defines how MCTP packets are framed over I2C/SMBus. This layer sits between the I2C driver and the SPDM Responder.\\n\\n## Folded Items\\n- **Real SMBus integration (MCU \u2194 BMC on hardware)** (scope item, L, medium confidence): Hardware integration testing is performed as part of transport layer validation. Acceptance criteria below capture the real-hardware validation requirements.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: I2C/SMBus slave driver (MCU as MCTP endpoint)\\n- RELATED_TO: libspdm Responder integration\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCTP packet encode/decode passes known test vectors (DSP0237 examples)\\n- [ ] Multi-packet message fragmentation and reassembly works correctly\\n- [ ] MCTP control messages (Get Endpoint ID, Get Message Type) handled\\n- [ ] MCU advertises SPDM message type support\\n- [ ] MCU and BMC exchange MCTP packets over real SMBus hardware\\n- [ ] No I2C bus errors or timeouts under normal operation on real hardware\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for MCTP packet encode/decode and fragmentation logic\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-l\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"L\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"MCTP packet encode/decode passes known test vectors (DSP0237 examples)\",\n            \"Multi-packet message fragmentation and reassembly works correctly\",\n            \"MCTP control messages (Get Endpoint ID, Get Message Type) handled\",\n            \"MCU advertises SPDM message type support\",\n            \"MCU and BMC exchange MCTP packets over real SMBus hardware\",\n            \"No I2C bus errors or timeouts under normal operation on real hardware\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for MCTP packet encode/decode and fragmentation logic\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"I2C/SMBus slave driver (MCU as MCTP endpoint)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] libspdm Responder integration\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nIntegrate libspdm v3.8.1 as the SPDM 1.2 Responder. Implement all required callbacks: transport encode/decode (MCTP), crypto operations (CASPER/Mbed TLS), measurement collection, certificate retrieval. Configure capabilities: CERT_CAP, CHAL_CAP, MEAS_CAP_SIG.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThis is the central integration point where all subsystems (crypto, transport, measurements, certificates) come together to form a complete SPDM 1.2 Responder. libspdm provides the protocol state machine; this Story implements the platform-specific callbacks.\\n\\n## Folded Items\\n- **Real SMBus integration (MCU \u2194 BMC on hardware)** (partial): Full SPDM 1.2 flow over real hardware and stress testing (repeated attestation cycles) are captured in acceptance criteria below.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCTP over SMBus transport layer\\n- RELATED_TO: Measurement engine, Certificate slot management, ResponseNotReady mechanism, Error handling\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Full SPDM 1.2 flow completes: GET_VERSION \u2192 GET_CAPABILITIES \u2192 NEGOTIATE_ALGORITHMS \u2192 GET_DIGESTS \u2192 GET_CERTIFICATE \u2192 CHALLENGE \u2192 GET_MEASUREMENTS\\n- [ ] SPDM version 1.2 negotiated successfully\\n- [ ] Capabilities advertised: CERT_CAP, CHAL_CAP, MEAS_CAP_SIG\\n- [ ] spdm_emu basic Requester flow passes end-to-end\\n- [ ] Full SPDM 1.2 flow completes over real SMBus hardware with BMC\\n- [ ] Stress test: repeated attestation cycles without failure on real hardware\\n- [ ] All libspdm callbacks implemented: transport, crypto, measurement, certificate\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for libspdm callback implementations\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: XL\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-xl\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"XL\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"Full SPDM 1.2 flow completes: GET_VERSION \u2192 GET_CAPABILITIES \u2192 NEGOTIATE_ALGORITHMS \u2192 GET_DIGESTS \u2192 GET_CERTIFICATE \u2192 CHALLENGE \u2192 GET_MEASUREMENTS\",\n            \"SPDM version 1.2 negotiated successfully\",\n            \"Capabilities advertised: CERT_CAP, CHAL_CAP, MEAS_CAP_SIG\",\n            \"spdm_emu basic Requester flow passes end-to-end\",\n            \"Full SPDM 1.2 flow completes over real SMBus hardware with BMC\",\n            \"Stress test: repeated attestation cycles without failure on real hardware\",\n            \"All libspdm callbacks implemented: transport, crypto, measurement, certificate\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for libspdm callback implementations\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\", \"MCTP over SMBus transport layer\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] ResponseNotReady mechanism for slow CASPER operations\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement SPDM ResponseNotReady error response for operations where CASPER crypto latency exceeds the SPDM response timeout. MCU returns ResponseNotReady with appropriate RDTExponent, Requester retries after delay.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe CASPER hardware accelerator, while faster than software crypto, may still exceed SPDM response timeouts for ECC P-256 sign operations. The ResponseNotReady mechanism (defined in SPDM 1.2 spec) allows the Responder to signal that it needs more time, preventing timeout failures.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: libspdm Responder integration\\n- RELATED_TO: CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS (latency data informs RDTExponent)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] ResponseNotReady returned when crypto operation is in progress\\n- [ ] RDTExponent correctly reflects expected CASPER latency (informed by benchmark data)\\n- [ ] Requester successfully retries and receives final response\\n- [ ] spdm_emu handles ResponseNotReady flow correctly\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for ResponseNotReady generation and retry handling\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"ResponseNotReady returned when crypto operation is in progress\",\n            \"RDTExponent correctly reflects expected CASPER latency (informed by benchmark data)\",\n            \"Requester successfully retries and receives final response\",\n            \"spdm_emu handles ResponseNotReady flow correctly\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for ResponseNotReady generation and retry handling\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"libspdm Responder integration\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] Error handling & SPDM error responses\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement comprehensive SPDM error response handling: invalid requests, unsupported commands, unexpected state transitions, truncated packets, wrong algorithm negotiation. Return appropriate SPDM ERROR response codes.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nRobust error handling is essential for a production SPDM Responder. The MCU must gracefully handle malformed or unexpected requests without crashing, and return spec-compliant error codes so the Requester can diagnose issues.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: libspdm Responder integration\\n- RELATED_TO: ResponseNotReady mechanism\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Invalid SPDM request returns appropriate ERROR response code\\n- [ ] Truncated packets handled without crash or buffer overflow\\n- [ ] Wrong algorithm in NEGOTIATE_ALGORITHMS returns error\\n- [ ] Out-of-sequence requests handled per SPDM 1.2 spec\\n- [ ] MCU remains operational after error conditions (no hang or reboot)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for all error scenarios (fuzz-style invalid inputs)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"Invalid SPDM request returns appropriate ERROR response code\",\n            \"Truncated packets handled without crash or buffer overflow\",\n            \"Wrong algorithm in NEGOTIATE_ALGORITHMS returns error\",\n            \"Out-of-sequence requests handled per SPDM 1.2 spec\",\n            \"MCU remains operational after error conditions (no hang or reboot)\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for all error scenarios (fuzz-style invalid inputs)\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"libspdm Responder integration\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"[SPDM] Secure Boot & Provisioning\",\n      \"description\": \"## Overview\\nThis epic covers MCU secure boot enablement, firmware update mechanisms, anti-rollback protection, and factory provisioning automation. It ensures the MCU itself is trustworthy (secure boot) and that each unit can be provisioned with a unique identity in manufacturing.\\n\\n## Functional Thread\\nMCU secure boot (+ debug lockdown) \u2192 Anti-rollback counters \u2192 MCU A/B firmware update\\nMCU secure boot + PUF key enrollment \u2192 Factory provisioning automation\\n\\n## Cross-Epic Dependencies\\n- MCU secure boot is BLOCKED_BY MCU project scaffolding ([SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration)\\n- Factory provisioning automation is BLOCKED_BY PUF key enrollment ([SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration)\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- What is the MCU firmware update delivery mechanism in Phase 3?\",\n      \"components\": [\"firmware\", \"tools\"],\n      \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\"],\n      \"stories\": [\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nEnable NXP LPC55S69 secure boot: program Root of Trust Key Hash (ROTKH) into CMPA, sign MCU firmware images, configure boot ROM to verify signature before execution. Unsigned or tampered images must be rejected.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe MCU is a trust anchor for SPDM attestation \u2014 if the MCU firmware itself is not authenticated, the entire attestation chain is compromised. Secure boot ensures only Cornelis-signed firmware runs on the MCU.\\n\\n## Folded Items\\n- **Debug lockdown (CMPA/CFPA configuration)** (scope item, M, medium confidence): Debug lockdown is configured on the same branch as secure boot since both involve CMPA/CFPA programming. Acceptance criteria below capture debug lockdown requirements.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake) \u2014 [SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration epic\\n- RELATED_TO: MCU A/B firmware update, Anti-rollback counters, Factory provisioning automation\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] ROTKH programmed in CMPA\\n- [ ] Signed MCU firmware boots successfully\\n- [ ] Unsigned MCU firmware is rejected by boot ROM\\n- [ ] Tampered (modified) signed image is rejected\\n- [ ] Secure boot verified via NXP SPSDK tools\\n- [ ] SWD/JTAG access disabled on production-configured unit (debug lockdown)\\n- [ ] Debug lockdown survives power cycle\\n- [ ] CMPA/CFPA configuration documented\\n- [ ] Development units retain debug access (separate configuration profile)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for image signing and verification tooling\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-l\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"L\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"ROTKH programmed in CMPA\",\n            \"Signed MCU firmware boots successfully\",\n            \"Unsigned MCU firmware is rejected by boot ROM\",\n            \"Tampered (modified) signed image is rejected\",\n            \"Secure boot verified via NXP SPSDK tools\",\n            \"SWD/JTAG access disabled on production-configured unit (debug lockdown)\",\n            \"Debug lockdown survives power cycle\",\n            \"CMPA/CFPA configuration documented\",\n            \"Development units retain debug access (separate configuration profile)\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for image signing and verification tooling\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] Anti-rollback counters (monotonic counter in CFPA)\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement anti-rollback protection using monotonic counters in the LPC55S69 CFPA. Each firmware update increments the counter; boot ROM rejects firmware with a version below the counter value.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nAnti-rollback prevents an attacker from downgrading MCU firmware to a version with known vulnerabilities. The monotonic counter in CFPA is a hardware-enforced mechanism that cannot be decremented.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\\n- RELATED_TO: MCU A/B firmware update mechanism\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Monotonic counter incremented on firmware update\\n- [ ] Boot ROM rejects firmware with version below counter\\n- [ ] Counter survives power cycle\\n- [ ] Counter cannot be decremented (hardware enforced)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for counter increment and version check logic\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-m\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"M\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"Monotonic counter incremented on firmware update\",\n            \"Boot ROM rejects firmware with version below counter\",\n            \"Counter survives power cycle\",\n            \"Counter cannot be decremented (hardware enforced)\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for counter increment and version check logic\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[FW] MCU A/B firmware update mechanism\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nImplement A/B (dual-bank) firmware update mechanism for the MCU. New firmware is written to inactive bank, verified, then activated. Fallback to previous bank on boot failure.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nA/B firmware update ensures the MCU can be updated in the field without bricking. If a new firmware image fails to boot, the MCU automatically falls back to the previous known-good image.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\\n- RELATED_TO: Anti-rollback counters\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] New firmware written to inactive bank and verified\\n- [ ] Boot switches to new bank after successful verification\\n- [ ] Automatic fallback to previous bank on boot failure\\n- [ ] Update mechanism works with signed images only (unsigned rejected)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for bank switching logic and fallback detection\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\n          \"components\": [\"firmware\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-l\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"L\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"New firmware written to inactive bank and verified\",\n            \"Boot switches to new bank after successful verification\",\n            \"Automatic fallback to previous bank on boot failure\",\n            \"Update mechanism works with signed images only (unsigned rejected)\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for bank switching logic and fallback detection\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        },\n        {\n          \"summary\": \"[TOOL] Factory provisioning automation (NXP SPSDK)\",\n          \"description\": \"## Overview\\nDevelop factory provisioning scripts using NXP SPSDK to automate: PUF enrollment, key derivation, device certificate generation and signing, certificate chain injection, CMPA/CFPA programming, secure boot enablement, and debug lockdown. Each unit gets a unique device identity.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nManufacturing requires a repeatable, automated provisioning workflow to ensure every unit is correctly provisioned with a unique identity and secure boot configuration. Manual provisioning is error-prone and does not scale.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: PUF key enrollment & device key derivation \u2014 [SPDM] Transport & Responder Integration epic\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\\n- RELATED_TO: Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates, Real certificate chain\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Single script provisions a unit end-to-end (PUF enrollment \u2192 cert generation \u2192 CMPA/CFPA programming \u2192 secure boot enablement)\\n- [ ] Each provisioned unit has unique device identity (cert + key)\\n- [ ] Provisioned unit boots securely\\n- [ ] Provisioned unit passes full SPDM attestation flow\\n- [ ] Provisioning workflow documented for manufacturing\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for provisioning script logic (mock SPSDK calls)\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: XL\",\n          \"components\": [\"tools\"],\n          \"labels\": [\"feature-planning\", \"confidence-medium\", \"complexity-xl\"],\n          \"complexity\": \"XL\",\n          \"confidence\": \"medium\",\n          \"acceptance_criteria\": [\n            \"Single script provisions a unit end-to-end\",\n            \"Each provisioned unit has unique device identity (cert + key)\",\n            \"Provisioned unit boots securely\",\n            \"Provisioned unit passes full SPDM attestation flow\",\n            \"Provisioning workflow documented for manufacturing\",\n            \"Unit tests pass for provisioning script logic\",\n            \"Code reviewed and merged\"\n          ],\n          \"dependencies\": [\"PUF key enrollment & device key derivation\", \"MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\"],\n          \"assignee\": null\n        }\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}"